-internet )

The Networking Thread

*Avery Pennarun, welcome to Stratechery.*

*AP:* Hi. Great to be here.

*I=E2=80=99m looking forward to learning more about Tailscale. I am a big u=
ser, albeit in an unconventional way, although I think there=E2=80=99s a wh=
ole host of us that use it in perhaps unexpected setups. I always like to o=
pen these interviews by learning more about the person I=E2=80=99m talking =
to, so tell me your story. Where=E2=80=99d you grow up? How=E2=80=99d you g=
et started in tech? Take me back to the beginning.*

*AP:* Well, let=E2=80=99s see. I was born and raised in Thunder Bay, Ontari=
o, which is the Northwest. Very cold region of Canada.

*Yeah. I have driven through there.*

*AP:* A lot of people say that. That=E2=80=99s the exact words they use and=
 that=E2=80=99s because there=E2=80=99s basically one highway that goes all=
 the way across Canada. So if you=E2=80=99re going to drive across Canada, =
you=E2=80=99re going to drive through Thunder Bay.

*There you go.*

*AP:* Some people stop on the way, it is the biggest stop for probably four=
 hours in any direction. So usually you need a bathroom break or a gas stop=
 or something like that.

*I will say that I stopped there, because I probably did.*

*AP:* Yeah, you probably stopped briefly, at least. It=E2=80=99s a nice pla=
ce, I actually quite like it. My dad brought home our first computer when I=
 was three years old, and I was very excited to mash the keys and stuff. I =
memorized my first program in Basic when I was five, so I could type it in =
whenever I wanted. It would ask my name, and it would print it out 10 times=
 or something like that and I was basically, hooked for life.

*And so that=E2=80=99s been the whole thing ever since. But if you look thr=
ough your career, you=E2=80=99ve been in networking for a long time. What w=
as it about that, specifically? How=E2=80=99d you go from basic =E2=80=9Cty=
pe my name=E2=80=9D to being obsessed with networking?*

*AP:* So the original motivation for networking was the fact that my sister=
 also became obsessed with computers, and she wanted to be online all the t=
ime and we only had one modem, and we had one university account, when neit=
her of us were in university, that we shared, that we would dial into the u=
niversity and use the modem, and we both really wanted to use it at the sam=
e time.

So I was playing with this thing called Linux, which had just come out at t=
he time, and I found out that there was networking stuff inside Linux, and =
if you played with a lot of settings, you could basically connect two compu=
ters through the one modem to make it work. And so I fiddled and fiddled an=
d fiddled, and I started =E2=80=94 we didn=E2=80=99t have any special netwo=
rking hardware. We had, at this time, a 386 and a 486, which is our new com=
puter.

*Did you get the new one or the old one, or did your sister claim the fast =
one?*

*AP:* Well, we traded off. My sister was big into IRCs ( https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/IRC ) , she was just IRCing constantly. So she was fine with th=
e 386 as long as it was in text mode and IRC, so I used that one as the rou=
ter with the modem, and then I used a serial port link between the two and =
I was able to Telnet ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telnet ) , at the time=
, from my 486 into the 386. Then we used a program called Term, which was t=
his sort of efficient multiplexer ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terminal_=
multiplexer ) , if you remember it.

*I do.*

*AP:* And we were both able to use network connections to the university. A=
nd that was neat, but then I wanted to transfer files between them without =
using floppy disks and the serial port connection was just no good. So we=
=E2=80=99re like, =E2=80=9COh, I heard about this thing called PLIP=E2=80=
=9D, Parallel Line IP ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_Line_Interne=
t_Protocol ) , so we got a special parallel cable. My dad was really good a=
t wiring things so we wired up a parallel cable that was wired appropriatel=
y for PLIP, and I used parallel line connection between them, which I think=
 I get about 100 or 200 kbps, something like that, which was faster.

*Amazing, yeah.*

*AP:* But it was like, =E2=80=9CNow I want more=E2=80=9D. And so I told my =
dad, =E2=80=9CHey, can we get network cards?=E2=80=9D, and he is like, =E2=
=80=9CWhat do you mean?=E2=80=9D, and I=E2=80=99m like, =E2=80=9CWell, I he=
ard about these things that you can use, and then they=E2=80=99re like high=
-speed connections between computers=E2=80=9D. We didn=E2=80=99t have a lot=
 of money so I said, I don=E2=80=99t care about the fastest networking card=
 or the best networking card or whatever, just get us two that are the same=
, and the right cable that goes with them and he=E2=80=99s like, =E2=80=9CA=
h, I know the place, I=E2=80=99m going to go to the electronic junk store=
=E2=80=9D, so he went off to the electronic junk store where they have all =
kinds of components, and he came back that day and he=E2=80=99s like, =E2=
=80=9CAvery, you=E2=80=99ll be so proud of me, I got two network cards, $10=
 each, plus $5 worth of cable, and I picked the biggest cards, because I fi=
gured they would be the best ones=E2=80=9D.

*(laughing) Oh no!*

*AP:* And that is apparently not how computers work. So these cards were fr=
om 1980, they actually literally said =E2=80=9CCopyright 1980=E2=80=9D on t=
hem, and they were ARCNET ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ARCNET ) , which =
was a networking technology that came out before Ethernet, and it was 2.5 m=
egabits.

But on the upside, these cards were so simple that they were a good platfor=
m to learn on, and there was no Linux driver for them, which kind of defeat=
ed part of my purpose. So then, I=E2=80=99m like, =E2=80=9COkay, well let=
=E2=80=99s figure out how to write a network driver, how hard can it be?=E2=
=80=9D, and here I am in grade 10, or something like that, trying to learn =
how to write network drivers for Linux. But it actually was pretty simple a=
t the time and these cards were really, really simple. You just poke a coup=
le programmable I/O ports into it, like move a packet from one machine to a=
nother, I=E2=80=99m like, =E2=80=9COkay, I can do this=E2=80=9D.

So I wrote a network driver for Linux, that=E2=80=99s how I got into kernel=
 development, and I actually got this thing working, and now I could transf=
er files between my computers at high speed.

*Did your driver actually make it into Linux, as a whole? Is it still out t=
here?*

*AP:* Oh, yeah, did it ever, and because I was a high school student with n=
othing better to do, my tech support turnaround time was amazing. So when p=
eople were emailing me, it=E2=80=99s like, =E2=80=9CHey, I needed to use AR=
CNET on Linux for some reason=E2=80=9D, because it turned out it was used b=
y ISPs, it was used, I think, still used in car factories and stuff. It=E2=
=80=99s a really reliable old protocol. And so there are people all over th=
e world using this ARCNET driver. So fast-forward another 10 years or so, a=
nd actually while I was in university, a company in Chicago that was that w=
as still making-

*This was at Waterloo, right?*

*AP:* Yeah, this was University of Waterloo. A company in Chicago that was =
still making network cards, they are ARCNET cards. They had upgraded them t=
o, I think, 10 megabits, which was amazing for ARCNET at the time, and thei=
r PCI and PCMCIA versions, and they=E2=80=99re like, =E2=80=9CAvery, there=
=E2=80=99s people using these things in factories, the old ISA ones don=E2=
=80=99t work anymore, because you can=E2=80=99t buy computers with ISA buse=
s, but they=E2=80=99ve got all these million dollar robots that are attache=
d to them. So we built these new devices, but they want to run Linux and yo=
ur driver doesn=E2=80=99t work with the PCI ARCNET cards, can you do it?=E2=
=80=9D. I=E2=80=99m like, =E2=80=9CWell, I guess. If you send me the spec s=
heets and stuff, I could probably do it=E2=80=9D, and they=E2=80=99re like,=
 =E2=80=9CWell, how much will it cost?=E2=80=9D, and I was a university stu=
dent, I didn=E2=80=99t know how much anything costs, so I said, =E2=80=9CWh=
at if we say a hundred dollars an hour? I can probably do it in roughly 60 =
hours, so that=E2=80=99s like $6,000=E2=80=9D.

So I faxed him a quote, because that was the thing you did at the time, and=
 he called me out a day later and he said, =E2=80=9CAvery was that quote pe=
r day or what?=E2=80=9D, and that=E2=80=99s when I knew I had been a little=
 bit too low. But you know what? I was still like, =E2=80=9CLook, I can do =
it in 60 hours at a hundred dollars an hour, that=E2=80=99s way more than I=
 expect to get paid as a university student=E2=80=9D. So we did the deal, t=
hey flew me down to Chicago, we talked about it a lot, the driver worked fo=
r them, and that got me into the technology business, and I just sort of co=
ntinued from there.

*That=E2=80=99s amazing, that is an all time great origin story, I=E2=80=99=
m glad we got into it. You started, I believe, a company in university, Net=
 Integration Technologies ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nitix ). Is that =
right?*

*AP:* That is correct.

*So what did that do?*

*AP:* That=E2=80=99s actually a great continuation of the same story.

So having now connected our two computers at home, so we could both share t=
he Internet, I ended up working at the first Internet provider in Thunder B=
ay that wasn=E2=80=99t the university, which also did a bunch of dial up an=
d stuff, and it was run by this guy who owned a computer store, who actuall=
y didn=E2=80=99t know how to run an Internet provider. So they tracked me d=
own, through a series of connections, to set up their ISP for them.

He also worked at this computer store and he did consulting for various com=
panies in the city, I didn=E2=80=99t have my driver=E2=80=99s license at th=
e time, so he would shuttle me around from place to place, and we would fix=
 their problems, and one of the observations I had over and over was there =
was these rooms full of people, and they all wanted to use this guy=E2=80=
=99s Internet service, which was brand new to Thunder Bay. And so there was=
 one computer in the corner with a modem, and they would line up to check t=
heir email, and I=E2=80=99m like, =E2=80=9CWell, this is silly, me and my s=
ister, at home, have a better setup than this=E2=80=9D.

I didn=E2=80=99t do much about it at the time, because it=E2=80=99s like, =
=E2=80=9COkay, if we set this up for every single person, it=E2=80=99s just=
 going to be a support nightmare and so on=E2=80=9D, but a couple of years =
later, I had been doing this all the way through high school, and I went of=
f to the University of Waterloo, and me and my roommate were thinking, =E2=
=80=9CWouldn=E2=80=99t it be good to find out what it=E2=80=99s like to sta=
rt a company, just as an experiment, so that we can make all the mistakes n=
ow and then when we graduate, we can decide if that=E2=80=99s really what w=
e want to do? So let=E2=80=99s do this for a few months and see what happen=
s=E2=80=9D.

We were brainstorming ideas for projects, and the project that came to mind=
 is all these companies that have a modem sitting in the corner, =E2=80=9CW=
ouldn=E2=80=99t it be great if they could just share that over the ethernet=
 network they already have? So why don=E2=80=99t we make a box that =E2=80=
=94 famous 19-year-old imagination =E2=80=94 we can just make it zero tech =
support and just plug-and-play, it works perfectly every time, so you don=
=E2=80=99t need to continue coming back and fixing it=E2=80=9D.

*It always words perfectly, doesn=E2=80=99t it?*

*AP:* Yeah, exactly. Why don=E2=80=99t we make just a super easy-to-use app=
liance that=E2=80=99ll let you share your network connection like this? Whi=
ch it turned out a really unusual idea at the time, nothing like that reall=
y existed.

So we built it, we assembled it from a PC. We bought a thousand dollars wor=
th of parts, and then sold it for $2,000, and these companies loved it, and=
 we sold five or ten of them or something like that, which was enough to pa=
y for the =E2=80=94 instead of taking a university co-op work term, we paid=
 our own salaries by selling these boxes, which was pretty good.

But then the problem was they loved it so much that they kept telling their=
 friends who would then phone us and say, =E2=80=9CHey, that company that m=
y friend works at has this box that lets you share your Internet connection=
, can I have one?=E2=80=9D. And it=E2=80=99s like, =E2=80=9CWell, it=E2=80=
=99s an instant thousand dollars if I assemble one device, and then ship it=
 to them, so I=E2=80=99m not going to say no to this, that=E2=80=99s a lot =
of beer and food money=E2=80=9D, so we kept selling those things.

Eventually it sort of escalated to the point =E2=80=94 I remember, at one p=
oint, I had to run out of an exam to answer a phone call, because somebody =
was having an urgent technical problem. I=E2=80=99m like, =E2=80=9CMaybe we=
 need somebody else to be involved in this company=E2=80=9D, so it sort of =
spiraled out of control from there. But Net Integration Technologies starte=
d from this, I just need to share my Internet, which well spiraled from the=
re.

*Well, it spiraled, it ended up being acquired.*

*AP:* Yeah. We grew to, I think, over a hundred employees, eventually got a=
cquired by IBM. And the reason IBM acquired us was it became the easiest wa=
y to install IBM DB2 and Lotus Domino, which were sort of famously difficul=
t to install and configure. And IBM, at the time, was really still feeling =
jealous of Microsoft about having taken over the PC business, basically, an=
d they were like, =E2=80=9CMicrosoft Exchange and Outlook are terrible, Lot=
us Notes is so much better, let=E2=80=99s try to get Lotus Notes to small b=
